  <h2>Where mockups are legitimate</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Product & feature demos.</strong> Show how your chat, support or messaging feature works before it ships, or without exposing a real customer's data.</li>
    <li><strong>UI and design mockups.</strong> Drop realistic conversations into app screenshots, Figma files and app-store imagery while the real integration is still in development.</li>
    <li><strong>Slide decks & pitches.</strong> Illustrate a user journey with a clean example instead of a messy real screenshot full of irrelevant chatter.</li>
    <li><strong>Onboarding & tutorials.</strong> Show the "ideal" example exchange so new users know what good looks like.</li>
    <li><strong>Example / illustrative testimonials.</strong> A clearly-labeled sample of the kind of feedback you get — used as a format illustration, not presented as a specific real person's words.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Where it crosses the line</h2>
  <p>
    The test is simple: <strong>would a reasonable viewer believe this is a specific real conversation, and would that belief be false?</strong> If yes, you're misleading them. Concretely, don't:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Invent a testimonial and attribute it to a real, named customer who never said it.</li>
    <li>Fabricate "proof" — a screenshot of support resolving an issue that was never resolved, or a chat that never happened, presented as evidence.</li>
    <li>Manufacture fake reviews or social proof (screenshots of praise from people who don't exist, passed off as genuine).</li>
    <li>Impersonate a real brand, person or their handle to make it look like they endorsed you.</li>
    <li>Fake numbers, results or claims inside the chat ("I made $10k in a week") that you can't back up.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Beyond ethics, invented testimonials and fabricated endorsements can violate advertising rules (for example, the FTC's guidance on endorsements and testimonials in the US) and platform policies. "It's just a mockup" is not a defense if you presented it as real.
  </p>

  <h2>The four rules for honest mockups</h2>

  <h3>1. Label it when there's any doubt</h3>
  <p>
    If a screenshot could be mistaken for a real, specific conversation, add a visible <em>"Illustrative example"</em> or <em>"Sample conversation"</em> caption. In demos, a quick "this is a mockup of the flow" line removes all ambiguity. Disclosure costs you nothing and protects you completely.
  </p>

  <h3>2. Use fictional identities</h3>
  <p>
    Use made-up names, generic avatars and placeholder handles — never a real customer's name, photo or account without written permission. If you're showing a testimonial format, make the person obviously generic ("Jordan M., Customer") rather than impersonating someone specific.
  </p>

  <h3>3. Keep claims truthful</h3>
  <p>
    The conversation can be invented; the <em>substance</em> shouldn't lie. If your mockup shows a feature, that feature should actually work that way. If it implies a result, that result should be real and typical. A demo that misrepresents what your product does is a problem no disclaimer fixes.
  </p>

  <h3>4. Don't fabricate social proof</h3>
  <p>
    Illustrating "here's the kind of message we get" is fine when it's clearly a format example. Manufacturing specific praise from invented users and presenting it as real customer feedback is not — that's fake reviews, full stop.
  </p>

