  <h2>A quick checklist before you publish</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Is this a specific claim that could be read as real? → Label it.</li>
    <li>Are the names, faces and handles fictional or permissioned? → They should be.</li>
    <li>Does the substance (feature behavior, results) match reality? → It must.</li>
    <li>Am I presenting invented praise as genuine customer feedback? → Don't.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Tick all four and you get the persuasive power of a chat screenshot with none of the risk.
  </p>

  <h2 id="ethics">The bottom line</h2>
  <p>
    Mockups are a normal, honest part of marketing and product work — the same way a stock photo or a wireframe is. The line isn't "real vs. fake," it's <strong>"honest vs. misleading."</strong> Illustrate freely; just don't dress up an invention as a specific real event or endorsement. Easy Chat Maker's export asks you to confirm your conversation is fictional for exactly this reason.
  </p>

